Date: 8/7/1850
Source: Letter
Author: GODLEY
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote:  It is customary here, & sometimes very profitable, to have sheep 'on thirds'; which means to send them to the station, & allow the owner of it half the wool, & 1/3d. of the increase for the trouble & expense of looking after them - the owner receives half the wool, & 2/3ds. of the increase, as profit on his capital.
Notes: 1850 July 8 Godley letter in 1971 Speeches and Documents 28

Date: 0/0/1853
Source: Adventures of a Surveyor
Author: ROCHFORT
Vol / Page: 27
Edition:
Quote: A settler will generally take sheep on thirds; that is, he takes the sheep on his run, and attends to them, finding labour: the party to whom the sheep belong gives him annually one-third of the increase and half the wool, besides paying for material for dressing in case of scab, &c.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1853
Source: Spring in the Canterbury Settlement, A
Author: ADAMS
Vol / Page: 68
Edition:
Quote:  or place his sheep `on thirds', as it is called; that is to say, may enter into an arrangement with the owner of some large sheep farm, to receive a certain proportion of the wool and of the increase, in lieu of rent.
Notes: (Griffiths Collection)

